04372nam a22007815i 9781442620971DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426209717 a10.3138/97814426209712doi  a(DE-B1597)465496  a(OCoLC)1013938790  a(OCoLC)944178949  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aD16b.M382 2004eb 7aHIS0160002bisacsh04a9012221 aMartin, Ged, eauthor.10aPast Futures :bThe Impossible Necessity of History /cGed Martin. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJoanne Goodman Lectures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Redefining History at the Centre of Debate -- t2. History versus the Past -- t3. The Impossibility of Explanation -- t4. The Moment of Decision -- t5. Past Futures -- t6. A Long Time in History -- t7. Significance -- t8. Objections, Review, and Tailpiece -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy nature, human beings seek to make sense of their past. Paradoxically, true historical explanation is ultimately impossible. Historians never have complete evidence from the past, nor is their methodology rigorous enough to prove causal links. Although it cannot be proven that 'A caused B,' by redefining the agenda of historical discourse, scholars can locate events in time and place history once again at the heart of intellectual activity.In Past Futures, Ged Martin advocates examining the decisions that people take, most of which are not the result of a 'process,' but are reached intuitively. Subsequent rationalizations that constitute historical evidence simply mislead. All historians can do is to locate them in time, to explain not why a decision was taken, but why then? To illustrate, Martin asks a number of questions: What is a 'long time' in history? Are we close to the past or remote from it? Is democracy a recent experiment, or proof of our arrival at the end of a journey through time? Can we engage in a historical dialogue with the past without making clear our own ethical standpoints? Although explanation is ultimately impossible, humankind can make sense of its location in time through the concept of 'significance,' a device for highlighting events and aspects of the past. In so doing, Martin suggests a radical new approach to historical discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aHistoriography. 0aHistoryxMethodology. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442620971423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442620971.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG